What is the quality control (QC) workflow?

Upon upload, interactive volcano plot and scatter plot (if the user upload input includes rep1 and rep2 values) will be generated. Hovering over each marker will show the corresponding gene in HGNC symbol.

Genes of interest can be searched for on the interactive plots using the search function on the side panel.

The initial FDR threshold for color scale is 0.1. Results are shown as a volcano plot where logFC values of the bait versus control condition are plotted on the x-axis and the negative log10 transformed P values of that enrichment are plotted on the y-axis. Interaction partners that are enriched in the experiment with an FDR < 0.1 are green, and interaction partners with an FDR >= 0.1 are blue. Upon selection of new FDR value on the left panel, the interactive plots will render with the new color scale reflecting new FDR threshold value.

Table on the right shows the count of interactors that are enriched in regions specified by the controllers on the left panel.



For convenience user is able to change the colors determined by FDR threshold using “color selection for markers.”



For convenience, markers can also be colored in grayscale, by ExAC pLI scores, or by user uploaded scores (details below).



Visualizing using the “ExAC” color scheme helps to identify proteins encoded by genes likely to be extremely intolerant to loss-of-function (LoF) variation using the ExAC pLI scores. Genes marked as pLI >= 0.9 are defined as extremely LoF intolerant set of genes. Genes marked as pLI < 0.9 are defined as LoF tolerant set of genes.



“User upload” color scheme allows user to upload genes and their associated scores. For example, user can upload external datasets such as Project Achilles, or RNA-Seq expression value associated with genes as text a text file.



Discrete color scale assigns different colors to each scores reported in user file and continuous color scale creates a gradient between the mininum and maximum scores reported. The user file must have the correct column headers ‘gene’ and ‘score.’

Here is an example of correct column headers and accepted values.



Upon user score input, the proteomics data will be visualized using the user uploaded score. The color theme can be changed using ‘color selection for markers.’ The example plot shown below is plotted using the YlGnBu (YellowGreenBlue) color theme.




Protein families removal

The “Protein families” option is a cleanup function designed to quality control the user uploaded data by removing protein family members considered as contaminants or sticky proteins. Protein family lists are taken from the HGNC database, curated by the HGNC appointed team. This feature is only available when the user uploads either HGNC approved symbol or UniProt accession numbers with logFC values for two replicates observed in the IP experiment.

The drop down menu shows all the protein families present in the HGNC database and multiple protein families can be selected. Any matching proteins in user database from the selected protein family will be highlighted and appear on the legend. The matching protein families coloring can be changed using ‘protein families color’ drop down menu.

If there are any matches, the “Remove selected PF from input” button will appear and user is then able to download an updated proteomics data where the proteins belonging to the chosen protein families are removed.




Overlay known protein interactors from InWeb

Further QC can be performed by identifying the known protein interaction partners from InWeb (download InWeb).

InWeb contains known protein-protein interactions from >40,000 articles and overlaying this information and the experimental data serves as QC.

Known interaction partners of the bait protein, as determined by overlaying InWeb data, are highlighted in yellow enabling users to quality control the data and to distinguish known and new interaction partners.
